# Week 3 — Industrial Process Simulation

## Overview

Week 3 focuses on implementing a **simulated industrial process** controlled by the PLC.
The goal of this phase is to create a realistic environment where the PLC interacts with process variables such as sensors and actuators.

A **tank level control system** was implemented to represent a simplified industrial process commonly used in manufacturing and water treatment systems.

The simulation allows the PLC to control the system behavior while generating data that will later be monitored by the SCADA system.

---

# Objectives

The main objectives of this phase include:

* Implement a simulated industrial process
* Develop PLC logic to control the process
* Simulate sensor values and actuator behavior
* Establish process safety conditions
* Validate system behavior during normal operation

---

# Industrial Process Model

The simulated plant represents a **water tank control system**.

This type of system is widely used in industrial environments such as:

* Water treatment facilities
* Chemical processing plants
* Manufacturing systems
* Storage tank monitoring

The PLC continuously monitors the tank level and controls the pump to maintain safe operating conditions.

---

# Process Components

| Component       | Description                           |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Tank            | Simulated water storage container     |
| Pump            | Controls water inflow                 |
| Level Sensor    | Measures tank water level             |
| Alarm Indicator | Triggers when tank reaches high level |

These components interact with the PLC through process variables.

---

# Process Logic

The PLC executes control logic that simulates how an industrial tank behaves.

### Control Rules

| Condition       | System Behavior          |
| --------------- | ------------------------ |
| Pump ON         | Tank level increases     |
| Pump OFF        | Tank level decreases     |
| Tank Full       | Pump automatically stops |
| Tank Level High | Alarm is triggered       |

This logic ensures the system operates within safe limits.

---

# PLC Process Variables

The following variables were used in the PLC logic to represent the industrial process.

| Variable      | Description                   |
| ------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Pump          | Controls water flow into tank |
| Tank_Level    | Represents tank sensor value  |
| High_Alarm    | Indicates high tank level     |
| Start_Command | Operator start signal         |
| Stop_Command  | Operator stop signal          |

These variables simulate the interaction between industrial sensors and actuators.

---

# Simulation Behavior

During normal operation:

* The pump increases the tank level when activated.
* When the pump is turned off, the tank level gradually decreases.
* If the tank level reaches the upper limit, the PLC stops the pump automatically.
* An alarm indicator activates when the tank reaches a critical level.

This behavior closely resembles real industrial tank control systems.

